challenging restarts, incurred additional social acceptance costs. Increasing costs undermined pro nuclear actors' ability to implement nuclear power policy and caused a rift inside the "nuclear village." Small nuclear safety administration reforms were, in fact, game changers for nuclear power politics in Japan. These findings contribute to the vibrant conversations about the rise of independent regulatory agencies, crisis as a mechanism for change, and the role of nuclear power amidst global interest in decarbonising energy supply.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFukushima Nuclear Disaster, Japan, 2011xPolitical aspects. 0aNuclear energyxGovernment policyzJapan. 0aNuclear energyxSafety regulationszJapan. 0aNuclear power plantsxSafety measuresxGovernment policyzJapan. 4aAsian Studies. 4aInternational Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aTechnology & Engineering / Power Resources / Nuclear.2bisacsh  anuclear safety in Japan, safety governance in Japan, Fukushima nuclear accident, nuclear power policy and safety, nuclear village, Nuclear Regulation Authority, nuclear disaster in Japan.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Engineering, Computer Sciences 2023 Englishz978311131912408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Engineering, Computer Sciences 2023z9783111318165oZDB-23-DEI40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150177005040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501770050423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cov